{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533405"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:35:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:35:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14781"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14781"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.16,0.09,0.58,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7472"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58570"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7472"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14781"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43972"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18285"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58570"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 46-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-month history of a painless swelling in his neck (Image). The swelling is slowly increasing in size. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has a 20 pack-year smoking history and drinks two cans of beer daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The neck examination reveals a firm swelling that moves with swallowing. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable. A core biopsy is performed and histology shows polygonal tumour cells with granular cytoplasm and amyloid in the stroma. The tumour cells are positive for calcitonin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Follicular carcinoma","Papillary carcinoma","Anaplastic carcinoma","Medullary carcinoma","Lymphoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a thyroid mass that has characteristic histological features of medullary thyroid carcinoma, including polygonal cells with granular cytoplasm, stromal amyloid deposits, and positive calcitonin immunostaining. Medullary thyroid carcinoma arises from the parafollicular C cells of the thyroid gland, which produce calcitonin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedullary carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is definitively diagnosed by the presence of calcitonin-positive cells and amyloid deposits in the stroma, which are pathognomonic features. This tumour accounts for about 5-10% of thyroid cancers and can occur sporadically or as part of Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia syndromes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFollicular carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows a different histological pattern with follicular differentiation and invasion through the capsule or blood vessels. It does not contain amyloid deposits or stain for calcitonin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPapillary carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E, the most common thyroid cancer, is characterised by papillary architecture and distinctive nuclear features including ground glass nuclei and nuclear grooves. It does not contain amyloid or stain for calcitonin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaplastic carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a highly aggressive undifferentiated tumour that typically presents in older patients with rapid growth and invasion. The histology shows pleomorphic cells without specific differentiation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E of the thyroid would show characteristic lymphoid cells on histology and would stain positive for lymphoid markers rather than calcitonin. It typically occurs in the setting of chronic lymphocytic thyroiditis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Medullary thyroid carcinoma is characterised histologically by polygonal cells with granular cytoplasm and amyloid deposits in the stroma.","Calcitonin immunostaining is diagnostic for medullary thyroid carcinoma.","A thyroid mass that moves with swallowing suggests thyroid origin."],"references":["Boucai L, Zafereo M, Cabanillas ME. Thyroid Cancer A Review. JAMA. 2024; 331:425-35."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43972"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14781"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21119"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21119"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/mAkofRNxg6LYsLAu95zBHReYFQlmCI.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/mAkofRNxg6LYsLAu95zBHReYFQlmCI.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":569,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43972"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-01T16:18:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-03T08:29:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7472"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58570"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups",